# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: n-formylmethionine-data-page
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, an **acid dissociation constant** (also known as **acidity constant**, or **acid-ionization constant**; denoted ⁠ $K_{a}$ ⁠) is a quantitative measure of the strength of an acid in solution.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] known as dissociation in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The chemical species HA is an acid that dissociates into A−, called the conjugate base of the acid, and a hydrogen ion, H+.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The system is said to be in equilibrium when the concentrations of its components do not change over time, because both forward and backward reactions are occurring at the same rate.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where quantities in square brackets represent the molar concentrations of the species at equilibrium.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, a hypothetical weak acid having *K*a = 10−5, the value of log *K*a is the exponent (−5), giving p*K*a = 5.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A lower *K*a corresponds to a weaker acid (an acid that is less dissociated at equilibrium).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The form p*K*a is often used because it provides a convenient logarithmic scale, and a lower p*K*a corresponds to a stronger acid.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid dissociation constant for an acid is a direct consequence of the underlying thermodynamics of the dissociation reaction; the p*K*a value is directly proportional to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the reaction.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of the p*K*a changes with temperature and can be understood qualitatively based on Le Chatelier's principle: when the reaction is endothermic, *K*a increases and p*K*a decreases with increasing temperature; the opposite is true for exothermic reactions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of p*K*a also depends on molecular structure of the acid in many ways.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, Linus Pauling proposed two rules: one for successive p*K*a of polyprotic acids (see Polyprotic acids below), and one to estimate the p*K*a of oxyacids based on the number of =O and −OH groups (see Factors that affect p*K*a values below).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other structural factors that influence the magnitude of the acid dissociation constant include inductive effects, mesomeric effects, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hammett type equations have frequently been applied to the estimation of p*K*a.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantitative behaviour of acids and bases in solution can be understood only if their p*K*a values are known.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In particular, the pH of a solution can be predicted when the analytical concentration and p*K*a values of all acids and bases are known; conversely, it is possible to calculate the equilibrium concentration of the acids and bases in solution when the pH is known.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These calculations find application in many different areas of chemistry, biology, medicine, and geology.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, many compounds used for medication are weak acids or bases, and a knowledge of the p*K*a values, together with the octanol-water partition coefficient, can be used for estimating the extent to which the compound enters the blood stream.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acid dissociation constants are also essential in aquatic chemistry and chemical oceanography, where the acidity of water plays a fundamental role.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In living organisms, acid–base homeostasis and enzyme kinetics are dependent on the p*K*a values of the many acids and bases present in the cell and in the body.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, a knowledge of p*K*a values is necessary for the preparation of buffer solutions and is also a prerequisite for a quantitative understanding of the interaction between acids or bases and metal ions to form complexes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Experimentally, p*K*a values can be determined by potentiometric (pH) titration, but for values of p*K*a less than about 2 or more than about 11, spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be required due to practical difficulties with pH measurements.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constant for this dissociation reaction is known as a dissociation constant.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid loses a proton, leaving a conjugate base; the proton is transferred to the base, creating a conjugate acid.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions of an acid HA, the base is water; the conjugate base is A− and the conjugate acid is the hydronium ion.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Brønsted–Lowry definition applies to other solvents, such as dimethyl sulfoxide: the solvent S acts as a base, accepting a proton and forming the conjugate acid SH+.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In solution chemistry, it is common to use H+ as an abbreviation for the solvated hydrogen ion, regardless of the solvent.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated hydronium ion rather than a proton.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The designation of an acid or base as "conjugate" depends on the context.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The hydroxide ion OH−, a well known base, is here acting as the conjugate base of the acid water.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acids and bases are thus regarded simply as donors and acceptors of protons respectively.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A broader definition of acid dissociation includes hydrolysis, in which protons are produced by the splitting of water molecules.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Lewis's original definition, an acid is a substance that accepts an electron pair to form a coordinate covalent bond.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid dissociation constant is a particular example of an equilibrium constant.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $\{X\}$ represents the activity, at equilibrium, of the chemical species X. $K^{\ominus }$ is dimensionless since activity is dimensionless.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Activities of the products of dissociation are placed in the numerator, activities of the reactants are placed in the denominator.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] See activity coefficient for a derivation of this expression.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $[{\text{HA}}]$ represents the concentration of HA and ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ is a quotient of activity coefficients.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To avoid the complications involved in using activities, dissociation constants are determined, where possible, in a medium of high ionic strength, that is, under conditions in which ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ can be assumed to be always constant.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the medium might be a solution of 0.1 molar (M) sodium nitrate or 3 M potassium perchlorate.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note, however, that all published dissociation constant values refer to the specific ionic medium used in their determination and that different values are obtained with different conditions, as shown for acetic acid in the illustration above.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When published constants refer to an ionic strength other than the one required for a particular application, they may be adjusted by means of specific ion theory (SIT) and other theories.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that in the context of metal-ligand complex formation, the equilibrium constants for the formation of metal complexes are usually defined as *association* constants.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In that case, the equilibrium constants for ligand protonation are also defined as association constants.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When discussing the properties of acids it is usual to specify equilibrium constants as acid dissociation constants, denoted by *K*a, with numerical values given the symbol p*K*a.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the other hand, association constants are used for bases.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, general purpose computer programs that are used to derive equilibrium constant values from experimental data use association constants for both acids and bases.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because stability constants for a metal-ligand complex are always specified as association constants, ligand protonation must also be specified as an association reaction.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The association constant for the formation of a supramolecular complex may be denoted as Ka; in such cases "a" stands for "association", not "acid".
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For polyprotic acids, the numbering of stepwise association constants is the reverse of the numbering of the dissociation constants.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] ⁠ R ⁠ is the gas constant and ⁠ T ⁠ is the absolute temperature.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus, for exothermic reactions, the standard enthalpy change, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠, is negative and *K* decreases with temperature.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For endothermic reactions, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ is positive and *K* increases with temperature.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where ⁠ $\Delta C_{p}$ ⁠ is the heat capacity change at constant pressure.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ may be taken to be constant over a small temperature range.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express each concentration value as the ratio c/c0, where c0 is the concentration in a [hypothetical] standard state, with a numerical value of 1, by definition.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express the concentrations on the mole fraction scale.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since mole fraction has no dimension, the quotient of concentrations will, by definition, be a pure number.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first and second options above give identical numerical values for an equilibrium constant.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is common practice in biochemistry to quote a value with a dimension as, for example, "*K*a = 30 mM" in order to indicate the scale, millimolar (mM) or micromolar (μM) of the concentration values used for its calculation.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid is classified as "strong" when the concentration of its undissociated species is too low to be measured.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Any aqueous acid with a p*K*a value of less than 0 is almost completely deprotonated and is considered a *strong acid*.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] All such acids transfer their protons to water and form the solvent cation species (H3O+ in aqueous solution) so that they all have essentially the same acidity, a phenomenon known as solvent leveling.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They are said to be *fully dissociated* in aqueous solution because the amount of undissociated acid, in equilibrium with the dissociation products, is below the detection limit.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Likewise, any aqueous base with an association constant p*K*b less than about 0, corresponding to p*K*a greater than about 14, is leveled to OH− and is considered a *strong base*.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nitric acid, with a p*K* value of around −1.7, behaves as a strong acid in aqueous solutions with a pH greater than 1.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At lower pH values it behaves as a weak acid.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values for strong acids have been estimated by theoretical means.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the p*K*a value of aqueous HCl has been estimated as −9.3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation, from which the following conclusions can be drawn.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In water, measurable p*K*a values range from about −2 for a strong acid to about 12 for a very weak acid (or strong base).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A buffer solution of a desired pH can be prepared as a mixture of a weak acid and its conjugate base.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice, the mixture can be created by dissolving the acid in water, and adding the requisite amount of strong acid or base.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the p*K*a and analytical concentration of the acid are known, the extent of dissociation and pH of a solution of a monoprotic acid can be easily calculated using an ICE table.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A polyprotic acid is a compound which may lose more than 1 proton.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Stepwise dissociation constants are each defined for the loss of a single proton.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The constant for dissociation of the first proton may be denoted as *K*a1 and the constants for dissociation of successive protons as *K*a2, etc.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Phosphoric acid, H3PO4, is an example of a polyprotic acid as it can lose three protons.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The species distribution diagram shows that the concentrations of the two ions are maximum at pH 5.5 and 10.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the difference between successive p*K* values is less than about four there is overlap between the pH range of existence of the species in equilibrium.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The smaller the difference, the more the overlap.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The case of citric acid is shown at the right; solutions of citric acid are buffered over the whole range of pH 2.5 to 7.5.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Pauling's first rule, successive p*K* values of a given acid increase (p*K*a2 > p*K*a1).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For oxyacids with more than one ionizable hydrogen on the same atom, the p*K*a values often increase by about 5 units for each proton removed, as in the example of phosphoric acid above.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It can be seen in the table above that the second proton is removed from a negatively charged species.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since the proton carries a positive charge extra work is needed to remove it, which is why p*K*a2 is greater than p*K*a1. p*K*a3 is greater than p*K*a2 because there is further charge separation.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When an exception to Pauling's rule is found, it indicates that a major change in structure is also occurring.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case of VO+2(aq), the vanadium is octahedral, 6-coordinate, whereas vanadic acid is tetrahedral, 4-coordinate.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This means that four "particles" are released with the first dissociation, but only two "particles" are released with the other dissociations, resulting in a much greater entropy contribution to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the first reaction than for the others.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For substances in solution, the isoelectric point (p*I*) is defined as the pH at which the sum, weighted by charge value, of concentrations of positively charged species is equal to the weighted sum of concentrations of negatively charged species.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case that there is one species of each type, the isoelectric point can be obtained directly from the p*K* values.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Take the example of glycine, defined as AH.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] There are two dissociation equilibria to consider.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*I* values for amino acids are listed at proteinogenic amino acid.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When more than two charged species are in equilibrium with each other a full speciation calculation may be needed.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When *K*a, *K*b and *K*w are determined under the same conditions of temperature and ionic strength, it follows, taking cologarithms, that p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] with sufficient accuracy for most practical purposes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In effect there is no need to define p*K*b separately from p*K*a, but it is done here as often only p*K*b values can be found in the older literature.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the reciprocal of an association constant for formation of the complex.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because the relationship p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a holds only in aqueous solutions (though analogous relationships apply for other amphoteric solvents), subdisciplines of chemistry like organic chemistry that usually deal with nonaqueous solutions generally do not use p*K*b as a measure of basicity.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Instead, the p*K*a of the conjugate acid, denoted by p*K*aH, is quoted when basicity needs to be quantified.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A higher value for p*K*aH corresponds to a stronger base.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the values p*K*aH (C5H5N) = 5.25 and p*K*aH ((CH3CH2)3N) = 10.75 indicate that (CH3CH2)3N (triethylamine) is a stronger base than C5H5N (pyridine).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amphoteric substance is one that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Carbonic acid equilibria are important for acid–base homeostasis in the human body.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amino acid is also amphoteric with the added complication that the neutral molecule is subject to an internal acid–base equilibrium in which the basic amino group attracts and binds the proton from the acidic carboxyl group, forming a zwitterion.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At pH less than about 5 both the carboxylate group and the amino group are protonated.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At high pH a second dissociation may take place.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus the amino acid molecule is amphoteric because it may either be protonated or deprotonated.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The water molecule may either gain or lose a proton.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where in aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated proton.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Often this is written as the hydronium ion H3O+, but this formula is not exact because in fact there is solvation by more than one water molecule and species such as H5O+2, H7O+3, and H9O+4 are also present.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The self-ionization constant of water, *K*w, is thus just a special case of an acid dissociation constant.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At that temperature both hydrogen and hydroxide ions have a concentration of 10−7 M.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high donor number, making it a strong Lewis base.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high dielectric constant (relative permittivity), making it a good solvent for ionic species.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values of organic compounds are often obtained using the aprotic solvents dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and acetonitrile (ACN).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] DMSO is widely used as an alternative to water because it has a lower dielectric constant than water, and is less polar and so dissolves non-polar, hydrophobic substances more easily.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a measurable p*K*a range of about 1 to 30.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acetonitrile is less basic than DMSO, and, so, in general, acids are weaker and bases are stronger in this solvent.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Some p*K*a values at 25 °C for acetonitrile (ACN) and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). are shown in the following tables.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Values for water are included for comparison.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ionization of acids is less in an acidic solvent than in water.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, hydrogen chloride is a weak acid when dissolved in acetic acid.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is because acetic acid is a much weaker base than water.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The unlikely geminal diol species CH3C(OH)+2 is stable in these environments.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions the pH scale is the most convenient acidity function.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other acidity functions have been proposed for non-aqueous media, the most notable being the Hammett acidity function, *H*0, for superacid media and its modified version *H*− for superbasic media.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aprotic solvents, oligomers, such as the well-known acetic acid dimer, may be formed by hydrogen bonding.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid may also form hydrogen bonds to its conjugate base.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This process, known as homoconjugation, has the effect of enhancing the acidity of acids, lowering their effective p*K*a values, by stabilizing the conjugate base.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Homoconjugation enhances the proton-donating power of toluenesulfonic acid in acetonitrile solution by a factor of nearly 800.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solutions, homoconjugation does not occur, because water forms stronger hydrogen bonds to the conjugate base than does the acid.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a compound has limited solubility in water it is common practice (in the pharmaceutical industry, for example) to determine p*K*a values in a solvent mixture such as water/dioxane or water/methanol, in which the compound is more soluble.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the example shown at the right, the p*K*a value rises steeply with increasing percentage of dioxane as the dielectric constant of the mixture is decreasing.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A p*K*a value obtained in a mixed solvent cannot be used directly for aqueous solutions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this is that when the solvent is in its standard state its activity is *defined* as one.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the standard state of water:dioxane mixture with 9:1 mixing ratio is precisely that solvent mixture, with no added solutes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To obtain the p*K*a value for use with aqueous solutions it has to be extrapolated to zero co-solvent concentration from values obtained from various co-solvent mixtures.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These facts are obscured by the omission of the solvent from the expression that is normally used to define p*K*a, but p*K*a values obtained in a *given* mixed solvent can be compared to each other, giving relative acid strengths.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The same is true of p*K*a values obtained in a particular non-aqueous solvent such a DMSO.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A universal, solvent-independent, scale for acid dissociation constants has not been developed, since there is no known way to compare the standard states of two different solvents.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Pauling's second rule is that the value of the first p*K*a for acids of the formula XO*m*(OH)*n* depends primarily on the number of oxo groups *m*, and is approximately independent of the number of hydroxy groups *n*, and also of the central atom X.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alternatively, various numerical formulas have been proposed including p*K*a = 8 − 5*m* (known as Bell's rule), p*K*a = 7 − 5*m*, or p*K*a = 9 − 7*m*.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The dependence on *m* correlates with the oxidation state of the central atom, X: the higher the oxidation state the stronger the oxyacid.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, p*K*a for HClO is 7.2, for HClO2 is 2.0, for HClO3 is −1 and HClO4 is a strong acid (p*K*a ≪ 0).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The increased acidity on adding an oxo group is due to stabilization of the conjugate base by delocalization of its negative charge over an additional oxygen atom.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This rule can help assign molecular structure: for example, phosphorous acid, having molecular formula H3PO3, has a p*K*a near 2, which suggested that the structure is HPO(OH)2, as later confirmed by NMR spectroscopy, and not P(OH)3, which would be expected to have a p*K*a near 8.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Inductive effects and mesomeric effects affect the p*K*a values.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A simple example is provided by the effect of replacing the hydrogen atoms in acetic acid by the more electronegative chlorine atom.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The electron-withdrawing effect of the substituent makes ionisation easier, so successive p*K*a values decrease in the series 4.7, 2.8, 1.4, and 0.7 when 0, 1, 2, or 3 chlorine atoms are present.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Hammett equation, provides a general expression for the effect of substituents.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alcohols do not normally behave as acids in water, but the presence of a double bond adjacent to the OH group can substantially decrease the p*K*a by the mechanism of keto–enol tautomerism.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ascorbic acid is an example of this effect.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The diketone 2,4-pentanedione (acetylacetone) is also a weak acid because of the keto–enol equilibrium.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aromatic compounds, such as phenol, which have an OH substituent, conjugation with the aromatic ring as a whole greatly increases the stability of the deprotonated form.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Structural effects can also be important.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The difference between fumaric acid and maleic acid is a classic example.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid is (E)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid, a *trans* isomer, whereas maleic acid is the corresponding *cis* isomer, i.e.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (Z)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid (see cis-trans isomerism).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid has p*K*a values of approximately 3.0 and 4.5.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] By contrast, maleic acid has p*K*a values of approximately 1.5 and 6.5.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this large difference is that when one proton is removed from the *cis* isomer (maleic acid) a strong intramolecular hydrogen bond is formed with the nearby remaining carboxyl group.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This favors the formation of the maleate H+, and it opposes the removal of the second proton from that species.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the *trans* isomer, the two carboxyl groups are always far apart, so hydrogen bonding is not observed.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Proton sponge, 1,8-bis(dimethylamino)naphthalene, has a p*K*a value of 12.1.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is one of the strongest amine bases known.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The high basicity is attributed to the relief of strain upon protonation and strong internal hydrogen bonding.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Effects of the solvent and solvation should be mentioned also in this section.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It turns out, these influences are more subtle than that of a dielectric medium mentioned above.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the expected (by electronic effects of methyl substituents) and observed in gas phase order of basicity of methylamines, Me3N > Me2NH > MeNH2 > NH3, is changed by water to Me2NH > MeNH2 > Me3N > NH3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Neutral methylamine molecules are hydrogen-bonded to water molecules mainly through one acceptor, N–HOH, interaction and only occasionally just one more donor bond, NH–OH2.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hence, methylamines are stabilized to about the same extent by hydration, regardless of the number of methyl groups.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In stark contrast, corresponding methylammonium cations always utilize **all** the available protons for donor NH–OH2 bonding.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Relative stabilization of methylammonium ions thus decreases with the number of methyl groups explaining the order of water basicity of methylamines.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The standard enthalpy change can be determined by calorimetry or by using the van 't Hoff equation, though the calorimetric method is preferable.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When both the standard enthalpy change and acid dissociation constant have been determined, the standard entropy change is easily calculated from the equation above.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the following table, the entropy terms are calculated from the experimental values of p*K*a and Δ*H*⊖.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The data were critically selected and refer to 25 °C and zero ionic strength, in water.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first point to note is that, when p*K*a is positive, the standard free energy change for the dissociation reaction is also positive.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Second, some reactions are exothermic and some are endothermic, but, when Δ*H*⊖ is negative *T*ΔS⊖ is the dominant factor, which determines that Δ*G*⊖ is positive.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Last, the entropy contribution is always unfavourable (Δ*S*⊖ < 0) in these reactions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ions in aqueous solution tend to orient the surrounding water molecules, which orders the solution and decreases the entropy.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The contribution of an ion to the entropy is the partial molar entropy which is often negative, especially for small or highly charged ions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The ionization of a neutral acid involves formation of two ions so that the entropy decreases (Δ*S*⊖ < 0).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the second ionization of the same acid, there are now three ions and the anion has a charge, so the entropy again decreases.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that the *standard* free energy change for the reaction is for the changes *from* the reactants in their standard states *to* the products in their standard states.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The free energy change *at* equilibrium is zero since the chemical potentials of reactants and products are equal at equilibrium.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The experimental determination of p*K*a values is commonly performed by means of titrations, in a medium of high ionic strength and at constant temperature.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A typical procedure would be as follows.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A solution of the compound in the medium is acidified with a strong acid to the point where the compound is fully protonated.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The solution is then titrated with a strong base until all the protons have been removed.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At each point in the titration pH is measured using a glass electrode and a pH meter.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constants are found by fitting calculated pH values to the observed values, using the method of least squares.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The total volume of added strong base should be small compared to the initial volume of titrand solution in order to keep the ionic strength nearly constant.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This will ensure that p*K*a remains invariant during the titration.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A calculated titration curve for oxalic acid is shown at the right.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Oxalic acid has p*K*a values of 1.27 and 4.27.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Therefore, the buffer regions will be centered at about pH 1.3 and pH 4.3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The buffer regions carry the information necessary to get the p*K*a values as the concentrations of acid and conjugate base change along a buffer region.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Between the two buffer regions there is an end-point, or equivalence point, at about pH 3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This end-point is not sharp and is typical of a diprotic acid whose buffer regions overlap by a small amount: p*K*a2 − p*K*a1 is about three in this example.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (If the difference in p*K* values were about two or less, the end-point would not be noticeable.) The second end-point begins at about pH 6.3 and is sharp.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This indicates that all the protons have been removed.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When this is so, the solution is not buffered and the pH rises steeply on addition of a small amount of strong base.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, the pH does not continue to rise indefinitely.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A new buffer region begins at about pH 11 (p*K*w − 3), which is where self-ionization of water becomes important.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is very difficult to measure pH values of less than two in aqueous solution with a glass electrode, because the Nernst equation breaks down at such low pH values.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To determine p*K* values of less than about 2 or more than about 11 spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be used instead of, or combined with, pH measurements.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the glass electrode cannot be employed, as with non-aqueous solutions, spectrophotometric methods are frequently used.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These may involve absorbance or fluorescence measurements.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In both cases the measured quantity is assumed to be proportional to the sum of contributions from each photo-active species; with absorbance measurements the Beer–Lambert law is assumed to apply.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC) may be used to determine both a p*K* value and the corresponding standard enthalpy for acid dissociation.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Software to perform the calculations is supplied by the instrument manufacturers for simple systems.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Aqueous solutions with normal water cannot be used for 1H NMR measurements but heavy water, D2O, must be used instead.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] 13C NMR data, however, can be used with normal water and 1H NMR spectra can be used with non-aqueous media.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantities measured with NMR are time-averaged chemical shifts, as proton exchange is fast on the NMR time-scale.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other chemical shifts, such as those of 31P can be measured.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For some polyprotic acids, dissociation (or association) occurs at more than one nonequivalent site, and the observed macroscopic equilibrium constant, or macro-constant, is a combination of micro-constants involving distinct species.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When one reactant forms two products in parallel, the macro-constant is a sum of two micro-constants, $K=K_{X}+K_{Y}.$ This is true for example for the deprotonation of the amino acid cysteine, which exists in solution as a neutral zwitterion HS−CH2−CH(NH+3)−COO−.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Similarly, a base such as spermine has more than one site where protonation can occur.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, mono-protonation can occur at a terminal −NH2 group or at internal −NH− groups.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The *K*b values for dissociation of spermine protonated at one or other of the sites are examples of micro-constants.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They cannot be determined directly by means of pH, absorbance, fluorescence or NMR measurements; a measured *K*b value is the sum of the K values for the micro-reactions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nevertheless, the site of protonation is very important for biological function, so mathematical methods have been developed for the determination of micro-constants.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a reactant undergoes two reactions in series, the macro-constant for the combined reaction is the product of the micro-constant for the two steps.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the quantitative treatment of systems involving acid–base equilibria in solution.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Many applications exist in biochemistry; for example, the p*K*a values of proteins and amino acid side chains are of major importance for the activity of enzymes and the stability of proteins.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Protein p*K*a values cannot always be measured directly, but may be calculated using theoretical methods.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions are used extensively to provide solutions at or near the physiological pH for the study of biochemical reactions; the design of these solutions depends on a knowledge of the p*K*a values of their components.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Important buffer solutions include MOPS, which provides a solution with pH 7.2, and tricine, which is used in gel electrophoresis.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffering is an essential part of acid base physiology including acid–base homeostasis, and is key to understanding disorders such as acid–base disorder.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The isoelectric point of a given molecule is a function of its p*K* values, so different molecules have different isoelectric points.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This permits a technique called isoelectric focusing, which is used for separation of proteins by 2-D gel polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions also play a key role in analytical chemistry.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] They are used whenever there is a need to fix the pH of a solution at a particular value.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Compared with an aqueous solution, the pH of a buffer solution is relatively insensitive to the addition of a small amount of strong acid or strong base.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The buffer capacity of a simple buffer solution is largest when pH = p*K*a.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In acid–base extraction, the efficiency of extraction of a compound into an organic phase, such as an ether, can be optimised by adjusting the pH of the aqueous phase using an appropriate buffer.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] At the optimum pH, the concentration of the electrically neutral species is maximised; such a species is more soluble in organic solvents having a low dielectric constant than it is in water.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This technique is used for the purification of weak acids and bases.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A pH indicator is a weak acid or weak base that changes colour in the transition pH range, which is approximately p*K*a ± 1.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The design of a universal indicator requires a mixture of indicators whose adjacent p*K*a values differ by about two, so that their transition pH ranges just overlap.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In pharmacology, ionization of a compound alters its physical behaviour and macro properties such as solubility and lipophilicity, log *p*).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, ionization of any compound will increase the solubility in water, but decrease the lipophilicity.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This is exploited in drug development to increase the concentration of a compound in the blood by adjusting the p*K*a of an ionizable group.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the understanding of coordination complexes, which are formed by the interaction of a metal ion, Mm+, acting as a Lewis acid, with a ligand, L, acting as a Lewis base.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] To determine the equilibrium constant for this reaction, in which the ligand loses a proton, the p*K*a of the protonated ligand must be known.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In practice, the ligand may be polyprotic; for example EDTA4− can accept four protons; in that case, all p*K*a values must be known.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In addition, the metal ion is subject to hydrolysis, that is, it behaves as a weak acid, so the p*K* values for the hydrolysis reactions must also be known.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Assessing the hazard associated with an acid or base may require a knowledge of p*K*a values.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, hydrogen cyanide is a very toxic gas, because the cyanide ion inhibits the iron-containing enzyme cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Hydrogen cyanide is a weak acid in aqueous solution with a p*K*a of about 9.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In strongly alkaline solutions, above pH 11, say, it follows that sodium cyanide is "fully dissociated" so the hazard due to the hydrogen cyanide gas is much reduced.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] An acidic solution, on the other hand, is very hazardous because all the cyanide is in its acid form.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Ingestion of cyanide by mouth is potentially fatal, independently of pH, because of the reaction with cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In environmental science acid–base equilibria are important for lakes and rivers; for example, humic acids are important components of natural waters.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] There are multiple techniques to determine the p*K*a of a chemical, leading to some discrepancies between different sources.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Well measured values are typically within 0.1 units of each other.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Data presented here were taken at 25 °C in water.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] More values can be found in the Thermodynamics section, above.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A table of p*K*a of carbon acids, measured in DMSO, can be found on the page on carbanions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The **Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical** (**ATC**) **Classification System** is a drug classification system that classifies the active ingredients of drugs according to the organ or system on which they act and their therapeutic, pharmacological and chemical properties.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Its purpose is an aid to monitor drug use and for research to improve quality medication use.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] It does not imply drug recommendation or efficacy.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] It is controlled by the World Health Organization Collaborating Centre for Drug Statistics Methodology (WHOCC), and was first published in 1976.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] This pharmaceutical coding system divides drugs into different groups according to the organ or system on which they act, their therapeutic intent or nature, and the drug's chemical characteristics.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Different brands share the same code if they have the same active substance and indications.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Each bottom-level ATC code stands for a pharmaceutically used substance, or a combination of substances, in a single indication (or use).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The ATC classification system is a strict hierarchy, meaning that each code necessarily has one and only one parent code, except for the 14 codes at the topmost level which have no parents.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The codes are semantic identifiers, meaning they depict information by themselves beyond serving as identifiers (namely, the codes depict themselves the complete lineage of parenthood).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] As of 7 May 2020, there are 6,331 codes in ATC; the table below gives the count per level.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The ATC system is based on the earlier Anatomical Classification System, which is intended as a tool for the pharmaceutical industry to classify pharmaceutical products (as opposed to their active ingredients).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] This system, confusingly also called ATC, was initiated in 1971 by the European Pharmaceutical Market Research Association (EphMRA) and is being maintained by the EphMRA and Intellus.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Its codes are organised into four levels.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The WHO's system, having five levels, is an extension and modification of the EphMRA's.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The first level of the code indicates the anatomical main group and consists of one letter.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The second level of the code indicates the therapeutic subgroup and consists of two digits.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The third level of the code indicates the therapeutic/pharmacological subgroup and consists of one letter.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The fourth level of the code indicates the chemical/therapeutic/pharmacological subgroup and consists of one letter.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The fifth level of the code indicates the chemical substance and consists of two digits.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The *Anatomical Therapeutic Chemical Classification System for veterinary medicinal products* (ATCvet) is used to classify veterinary drugs.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] ATCvet codes can be created by placing the letter Q in front of the ATC code of most human medications.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] For example, furosemide for veterinary use has the code **Q**C03CA01.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Some codes are used exclusively for veterinary drugs, such as *QI Immunologicals*, *QJ51 Antibacterials for intramammary use* or *QN05AX90 amperozide*.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The Herbal ATC system (HATC) is an ATC classification of herbal substances; it differs from the regular ATC system by using 4 digits instead of 2 at the 5th level group.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The herbal classification is not adopted by WHO.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The Uppsala Monitoring Centre is responsible for the Herbal ATC classification, and it is part of the WHODrug Global portfolio available by subscription.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] The ATC system also includes defined daily doses (DDDs) for many drugs.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] This is a measurement of drug consumption based on the usual daily dose for a given drug.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] National issues of the ATC classification, such as the German *Anatomisch-therapeutisch-chemische Klassifikation mit Tagesdosen*, may include additional codes and DDDs not present in the WHO version.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] ATC follows guidelines in creating new codes for newly approved drugs.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] An application is submitted to WHO for ATC classification and DDD assignment.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] A preliminary or temporary code is assigned and published on the website and in the *WHO Drug Information* for comment or objection.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] New ATC/DDD codes are discussed at the semi-annual Working Group meeting.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] If accepted it becomes a final decision and published semi-annually on the website and *WHO Drug Information* and implemented in the annual print/on-line ACT/DDD Index on January 1.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] Changes to existing ATC/DDD follow a similar process to become temporary codes and if accepted become a final decision as ATC/DDD alterations.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] ATC and DDD alterations are only valid and implemented in the coming annual updates; the original codes must continue until the end of the year.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/anatomical-therapeutic-chemical-classification-system] An updated version of the complete on-line/print ATC index with DDDs is published annually on January 1.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon is the 15th most abundant element in the Earth's crust, and the fourth most abundant element in the universe by mass after hydrogen, helium, and oxygen.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon's abundance, its unique diversity of organic compounds, and its unusual ability to form polymers at the temperatures commonly encountered on Earth, enables it to serve as the common element of all known life.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It is the second most abundant element in the human body by mass (about 18.5%) after oxygen.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The atoms of carbon can bond together in diverse ways, resulting in various allotropes of carbon.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Well-known allotropes include graphite, diamond, amorphous carbon, and fullerenes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The physical properties of carbon vary widely with the allotropic form.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] For example, graphite is opaque and black, while diamond is highly transparent.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Graphite is soft enough to form a streak on paper (hence its name, from the Greek verb "γράφειν" which means "to write"), while diamond is the hardest naturally occurring material known.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Graphite is a good electrical conductor while diamond has a low electrical conductivity.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Under normal conditions, diamond, carbon nanotubes, and graphene have the highest thermal conductivities of all known materials.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] All carbon allotropes are solids under normal conditions, with graphite being the most thermodynamically stable form at standard temperature and pressure.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] They are chemically resistant and require high temperature to react even with oxygen.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The most common oxidation state of carbon in inorganic compounds is +4, while +2 is found in carbon monoxide and transition metal carbonyl complexes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The largest sources of inorganic carbon are limestones, dolomites and carbon dioxide, but significant quantities occur in organic deposits of coal, peat, oil, and methane clathrates.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon forms a vast number of compounds, with about two hundred million having been described and indexed; and yet that number is still only a fraction of the number of theoretically possible compounds under standard conditions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon in its solid state exists in several allotropes, including graphite, a soft, black, and slippery material, and diamond, the hardest naturally occurring substance.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] This variation in physical properties arises from differences in atomic arrangement: graphite consists of layers of hexagonally arranged carbon atoms, while diamond features a rigid three-dimensional lattice.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Chemically, carbon is notable for its ability to form stable chemical bonds with many elements, particularly with other carbon atoms, and is capable of forming multiple stable covalent bonds with suitable multivalent atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon is a component element in the large majority of all chemical compounds, with about two hundred million examples having been described in the published chemical literature.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon also has the highest sublimation point of all elements.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Compared to its well-known solid allotropes, the liquid and gaseous phases of carbon are far less studied.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In the vapor phase, some of the carbon is in the form of highly reactive diatomic carbon (also known as dicarbon, with a chemical formula of C2).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The liquid phase of carbon is a dark, mobile, and reflective liquid that can only exist above 4,000 K (3,730 °C; 6,740 °F) and under pressures exceeding 100 atmospheres.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon is the sixth element, with a ground-state electron configuration of 1s22s22p2, of which the four outer electrons are valence electrons.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Its first four ionisation energies, 1086.5, 2352.6, 4620.5 and 6222.7 kJ/mol, are much higher than those of the heavier group-14 elements.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The electronegativity of carbon is 2.5, significantly higher than the heavier group-14 elements (1.8–1.9), but close to most of the nearby nonmetals, as well as some of the second- and third-row transition metals.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon's covalent radii are normally taken as 77.2 pm (C−C), 66.7 pm (C=C) and 60.3 pm (C≡C), although these may vary depending on coordination number and what the carbon is bonded to.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In general, covalent radius decreases with lower coordination number and higher bond order.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Graphite is much more reactive than diamond at standard conditions, despite being more thermodynamically stable, as its delocalised pi system is much more vulnerable to attack.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] For example, graphite can be oxidised by hot concentrated nitric acid at standard conditions to mellitic acid, C6(CO2H)6, which preserves the hexagonal units of graphite while breaking up the larger structure.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon-based compounds form the basis of all known life on Earth, and the carbon-nitrogen-oxygen cycle provides a small portion of the energy produced by the Sun, and most of the energy in larger stars (e.g.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Although it forms an extraordinary variety of compounds, most forms of carbon are comparatively unreactive under normal conditions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] At standard temperature and pressure, it resists all but the strongest oxidizers.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It does not react with sulfuric acid, hydrochloric acid, chlorine or any alkalis.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] At elevated temperatures, carbon reacts with oxygen to form carbon oxides and will rob oxygen from metal oxides to leave the elemental metal.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon combines with some metals at high temperatures to form metallic carbides, such as the iron carbide cementite in steel and tungsten carbide, widely used as an abrasive and for making hard tips for cutting tools.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Atomic carbon is a very short-lived species and, therefore, carbon is stabilized in various multi-atomic structures with diverse molecular configurations called allotropes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The three relatively well-known allotropes of carbon are amorphous carbon, graphite, and diamond.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Once considered exotic, fullerenes are nowadays commonly synthesized and used in research; they include buckyballs, carbon nanotubes, carbon nanobuds and nanofibers.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Several other exotic allotropes have also been discovered, such as lonsdaleite, glassy carbon, carbon nanofoam and linear acetylenic carbon (carbyne).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Graphene is a two-dimensional sheet of carbon with the atoms arranged in a hexagonal lattice.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] As of 2009, graphene appears to be the strongest material ever tested.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The process of separating it from graphite will require some further technological development before it is economical for industrial processes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] If successful, graphene could be used in the construction of a space elevator.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It could also be used to safely store hydrogen for use in a hydrogen based engine in cars.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The amorphous form is an assortment of carbon atoms in a non-crystalline, irregular, glassy state, not held in a crystalline macrostructure.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It is present as a powder, and is the main constituent of substances such as charcoal, lampblack (soot), and activated carbon.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] At normal pressures, carbon takes the form of graphite, in which each atom is bonded trigonally to three others in a plane composed of fused hexagonal rings, just like those in aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The resulting network is 2-dimensional, and the resulting flat sheets are stacked and loosely bonded through weak van der Waals forces.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] This gives graphite its softness and its cleaving properties (the sheets slip easily past one another).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Because of the delocalization of one of the outer electrons of each atom to form a π-cloud, graphite conducts electricity, but only in the plane of each covalently bonded sheet.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] This results in a lower bulk electrical conductivity for carbon than for most metals.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The delocalization also accounts for the energetic stability of graphite over diamond at room temperature.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] At very high pressures, carbon forms the more compact allotrope, diamond, having nearly twice the density of graphite.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Here, each atom is bonded tetrahedrally to four others, forming a 3-dimensional network of puckered six-membered rings of atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Diamond has the same cubic structure as silicon and germanium, and because of the strength of the carbon-carbon bonds, it is the hardest naturally occurring substance measured by resistance to scratching.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Contrary to the popular belief that *"diamonds are forever"*, they are thermodynamically unstable (Δf*G*°(diamond, 298 K) = 2.9 kJ/mol) under normal conditions (298 K, 105 Pa) and should theoretically transform into graphite.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] But due to a high activation energy barrier, the transition into graphite is so slow at normal temperature that it is unnoticeable.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] However, at very high temperatures diamond will turn into graphite, and diamonds can burn up in a house fire.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The bottom left corner of the phase diagram for carbon has not been scrutinized experimentally.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Under some conditions, carbon crystallizes as lonsdaleite, a hexagonal crystal lattice with all atoms covalently bonded and properties similar to those of diamond.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Fullerenes are a synthetic crystalline formation with a graphite-like structure, but in place of flat hexagonal cells only, some of the cells of which fullerenes are formed may be pentagons, nonplanar hexagons, or even heptagons of carbon atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The sheets are thus warped into spheres, ellipses, or cylinders.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The properties of fullerenes (split into buckyballs, buckytubes, and nanobuds) have not yet been fully analyzed and represent an intense area of research in nanomaterials.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The names *fullerene* and *buckyball* are given after Richard Buckminster Fuller, popularizer of geodesic domes, which resemble the structure of fullerenes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The buckyballs are fairly large molecules formed completely of carbon bonded trigonally, forming spheroids (the best-known and simplest is the soccerball-shaped C60 buckminsterfullerene).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon nanotubes (buckytubes) are structurally similar to buckyballs, except that each atom is bonded trigonally in a curved sheet that forms a hollow cylinder.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Nanobuds were first reported in 2007 and are hybrid buckytube/buckyball materials (buckyballs are covalently bonded to the outer wall of a nanotube) that combine the properties of both in a single structure.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Of the other discovered allotropes, carbon nanofoam is a ferromagnetic allotrope discovered in 1997.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It consists of a low-density cluster-assembly of carbon atoms strung together in a loose three-dimensional web, in which the atoms are bonded trigonally in six- and seven-membered rings.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It is among the lightest known solids, with a density of about 2 kg/m3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Similarly, glassy carbon contains a high proportion of closed porosity, but contrary to normal graphite, the graphitic layers are not stacked like pages in a book, but have a more random arrangement.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Linear acetylenic carbon has the chemical structure −(C≡C)n− .
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon in this modification is linear with *sp* orbital hybridization, and is a polymer with alternating single and triple bonds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] This carbyne is of considerable interest to nanotechnology as its Young's modulus is 40 times that of the hardest known material – diamond.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In 2015, a team at the North Carolina State University announced the development of another allotrope they have dubbed Q-carbon, created by a high-energy low-duration laser pulse on amorphous carbon dust.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Q-carbon is reported to exhibit ferromagnetism, fluorescence, and a hardness superior to diamonds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Isotopes of carbon are atomic nuclei that contain six protons plus a number of neutrons (varying from 2 to 16).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon has two stable, naturally occurring isotopes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The isotope carbon-12 (12C) forms 98.93% of the carbon on Earth, while carbon-13 (13C) forms the remaining 1.07%.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The concentration of 12C is further increased in biological materials because biochemical reactions discriminate against 13C.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In 1961, the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) adopted the isotope carbon-12 as the basis for atomic weights.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Identification of carbon in nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) experiments is done with the isotope 13C.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon-14 (14C) is a naturally occurring radioisotope, created in the upper atmosphere (lower stratosphere and upper troposphere) by interaction of nitrogen with cosmic rays.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It is found in trace amounts on Earth of 1 part per trillion (0.0000000001%) or more, mostly confined to the atmosphere and superficial deposits, particularly of peat and other organic materials.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] This isotope decays by 0.158 MeV β− emission.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Because of its relatively short half-life of 5700±30 years, 14C is virtually absent in ancient rocks.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The amount of 14C in the atmosphere and in living organisms is almost constant, but decreases predictably in their bodies after death.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] This principle is used in radiocarbon dating, invented in 1949, which has been used extensively to determine the age of carbonaceous materials with ages up to about 40,000 years.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] There are 15 known isotopes of carbon and the shortest-lived of these is 8C which decays through proton emission and has a half-life of 3.5×10−21 s.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The exotic 19C exhibits a nuclear halo, which means its radius is appreciably larger than would be expected if the nucleus were a sphere of constant density.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon is the fourth most abundant chemical element in the observable universe by mass after hydrogen, helium, and oxygen.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Some meteorites contain microscopic diamonds that were formed when the Solar System was still a protoplanetary disk.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Microscopic diamonds may also be formed by the intense pressure and high temperature at the sites of meteorite impacts.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In 2014 NASA announced a greatly upgraded database for tracking polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAHs) in the universe.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] More than 20% of the carbon in the universe may be associated with PAHs, complex compounds of carbon and hydrogen without oxygen.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] These compounds figure in the PAH world hypothesis where they are hypothesized to have a role in abiogenesis and formation of life.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] PAHs seem to have been formed "a couple of billion years" after the Big Bang, are widespread throughout the universe, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It has been estimated that the solid earth as a whole contains 730 ppm of carbon, with 2000 ppm in the core and 120 ppm in the combined mantle and crust.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Since the mass of the earth is 5.972×1024 kg, this would imply 4360 million gigatonnes of carbon.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] This is much more than the amount of carbon in the oceans or atmosphere (below).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In combination with oxygen in carbon dioxide, carbon is found in the Earth's atmosphere (approximately 900 gigatonnes of carbon — each ppm corresponds to 2.13 Gt) and dissolved in all water bodies (approximately 36,000 gigatonnes of carbon).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon in the biosphere has been estimated at 550 gigatonnes but with a large uncertainty, due mostly to a huge uncertainty in the amount of terrestrial deep subsurface bacteria.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Hydrocarbons (such as coal, petroleum, and natural gas) contain carbon as well.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Coal "reserves" (not "resources") amount to around 900 gigatonnes with perhaps 18,000 Gt of resources.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Proven sources of natural gas are about 175×1012 cubic metres (containing about 105 gigatonnes of carbon), but studies estimate another 900×1012 cubic metres of "unconventional" deposits such as shale gas, representing about 540 gigatonnes of carbon.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon is also found in methane hydrates in polar regions and under the seas.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Various estimates put this carbon between 500, 2500, or 3,000 Gt.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] According to one source, in the period from 1751 to 2008 about 347 gigatonnes of carbon were released as carbon dioxide to the atmosphere from burning of fossil fuels.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Another source puts the amount added to the atmosphere for the period since 1750 at 879 Gt, and the total going to the atmosphere, sea, and land (such as peat bogs) at almost 2,000 Gt.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon is a constituent (about 12% by mass) of the very large masses of carbonate rock (limestone, dolomite, marble, and others).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Coal is very rich in carbon (anthracite contains 92–98%) and is the largest commercial source of mineral carbon, accounting for 4,000 gigatonnes or 80% of fossil fuel.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] As for individual carbon allotropes, graphite is found in large quantities in China, Russia, Mexico, Canada, and India.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Natural diamonds occur in the rock kimberlite, found in ancient volcanic "necks", or "pipes".
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Most diamond deposits are in Africa, notably in South Africa, Namibia, Botswana, the Republic of the Congo, and Angola.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Diamond deposits have also been found in Arkansas, Canada, the Russian Arctic, Brazil, and in Northern and Western Australia.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Diamonds are found naturally, but about 90% of all industrial diamonds used in the U.S. are now manufactured.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon-14 is formed in upper layers of the troposphere and the stratosphere at altitudes of 9–15 km by a reaction that is precipitated by cosmic rays.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Thermal neutrons are produced that collide with the nuclei of nitrogen-14, forming carbon-14 and a proton.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] As such, 1.5%×10−10 of atmospheric carbon dioxide contains carbon-14.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon-rich asteroids are relatively preponderant in the outer parts of the asteroid belt in the Solar System.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] These asteroids have not yet been directly sampled by scientists.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The asteroids can be used in hypothetical space-based carbon mining, which may be possible in the future, but is currently technologically impossible.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Formation of the carbon atomic nucleus occurs within a giant or supergiant star through the triple-alpha process.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The triple-alpha process happens in conditions of temperatures over 100 megakelvins and helium concentration that the rapid expansion and cooling of the early universe prohibited, and therefore no significant carbon was created during the Big Bang.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] According to current physical cosmology theory, carbon is formed in the interiors of stars on the horizontal branch.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] When massive stars die as supernova, the carbon is scattered into space as dust.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] This dust becomes component material for the formation of the next-generation star systems with accreted planets.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The Solar System is one such star system with an abundance of carbon, enabling the existence of life as we know it.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It is the opinion of most scholars that all the carbon in the Solar System and the Milky Way comes from dying stars.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The CNO cycle is an additional hydrogen fusion mechanism that powers stars, wherein carbon operates as a catalyst.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Rotational transitions of various isotopic forms of carbon monoxide (for example, 12CO, 13CO, and 18CO) are detectable in the submillimeter wavelength range, and are used in the study of newly forming stars in molecular clouds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Under terrestrial conditions, conversion of one element to another is very rare.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Therefore, the amount of carbon on Earth is effectively constant.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Thus, processes that use carbon must obtain it from somewhere and dispose of it somewhere else.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The paths of carbon in the environment form the carbon cycle.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] For example, photosynthetic plants draw carbon dioxide from the atmosphere (or seawater) and build it into biomass, as in the Calvin cycle, a process of carbon fixation.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Some of this biomass is eaten by animals, while some carbon is exhaled by animals as carbon dioxide.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The carbon cycle is considerably more complicated than this short loop; for example, some carbon dioxide is dissolved in the oceans; if bacteria do not consume it, dead plant or animal matter may become petroleum or coal, which releases carbon when burned.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon can form very long chains of interconnecting carbon–carbon bonds, a property that is called catenation.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon-carbon bonds are strong and stable.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Through catenation, carbon forms a countless number of compounds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] A tally of unique compounds shows that more contain carbon than do not.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The simplest form of an organic molecule is the hydrocarbon—a large family of organic molecules that are composed of hydrogen atoms bonded to a chain of carbon atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] A hydrocarbon backbone can be substituted by other atoms, known as heteroatoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Common heteroatoms that appear in organic compounds include oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, phosphorus, and the nonradioactive halogens, as well as the metals lithium and magnesium.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Organic compounds containing bonds to metal are known as organometallic compounds (*see below*).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Certain groupings of atoms, often including heteroatoms, recur in large numbers of organic compounds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] These collections, known as *functional groups*, confer common reactivity patterns and allow for the systematic study and categorization of organic compounds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Chain length, shape and functional groups all affect the properties of organic molecules.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In most stable compounds of carbon (and nearly all stable *organic* compounds), carbon obeys the octet rule and is *tetravalent*, meaning that a carbon atom forms a total of four covalent bonds (which may include double and triple bonds).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon occurs in all known organic life and is the basis of organic chemistry.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] When united with hydrogen, it forms various hydrocarbons that are important to industry as refrigerants, lubricants, solvents, as chemical feedstock for the manufacture of plastics and petrochemicals, and as fossil fuels.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] When combined with oxygen and hydrogen, carbon can form many groups of important biological compounds including sugars, lignans, chitins, alcohols, fats, aromatic esters, carotenoids and terpenes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] With nitrogen, it forms alkaloids, and with the addition of sulfur also it forms antibiotics, amino acids, and rubber products.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] With the addition of phosphorus to these other elements, it forms DNA and RNA, the chemical-code carriers of life, and adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the most important energy-transfer molecule in all living cells.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Norman Horowitz, head of the Mariner and Viking missions to Mars (1965–1976), considered that the unique characteristics of carbon made it unlikely that any other element could replace carbon, even on another planet, to generate the biochemistry necessary for life.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Among these are the simple oxides of carbon.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The most prominent oxide is carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] This was once the principal constituent of the paleoatmosphere, but is a minor component of the Earth's atmosphere today.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Dissolved in water, it forms carbonic acid (H 2CO 3), but as most compounds with multiple single-bonded oxygens on a single carbon it is unstable.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Through this intermediate, though, resonance-stabilized carbonate ions are produced.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Some important minerals are carbonates, notably calcite.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The other common oxide is carbon monoxide (CO).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It is formed by incomplete combustion, and is a colorless, odorless gas.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The molecules each contain a triple bond and are fairly polar, resulting in a tendency to bind permanently to hemoglobin molecules, displacing oxygen, which has a lower binding affinity.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Cyanide (CN−) has a similar structure, but behaves much like a halide ion (pseudohalogen).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] For example, it can form the nitride cyanogen molecule ((CN)2), similar to diatomic halides.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Likewise, the heavier analog of cyanide, cyaphide (CP−), is also considered inorganic, though most simple derivatives are highly unstable.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Other uncommon oxides are carbon suboxide (C 3O 2), the unstable dicarbon monoxide (C2O), carbon trioxide (CO3), cyclopentanepentone (C5O5), cyclohexanehexone (C6O6), and mellitic anhydride (C12O9).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] However, mellitic anhydride is the triple acyl anhydride of mellitic acid; moreover, it contains a benzene ring.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Thus, many chemists consider it to be organic.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] With reactive metals, such as tungsten, carbon forms either carbides (C4−) or acetylides (C2− 2) to form alloys with high melting points.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] These anions are also associated with methane and acetylene, both very weak acids.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] With an electronegativity of 2.5, carbon prefers to form covalent bonds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] A few carbides are covalent lattices, like carborundum (SiC), which resembles diamond.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Nevertheless, even the most polar and salt-like of carbides are not completely ionic compounds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Organometallic compounds by definition contain at least one carbon-metal covalent bond.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Many metal carbonyls and metal cyanides exist (for example, tetracarbonylnickel and potassium ferricyanide); some workers consider metal carbonyl and cyanide complexes without other carbon ligands to be purely inorganic, and not organometallic.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] However, most organometallic chemists consider metal complexes with any carbon ligand, even 'inorganic carbon' (e.g., carbonyls, cyanides, and certain types of carbides and acetylides) to be organometallic in nature.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Metal complexes containing organic ligands without a carbon-metal covalent bond (e.g., metal carboxylates) are termed *metalorganic* compounds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] While carbon is understood to strongly prefer formation of four covalent bonds, other exotic bonding schemes are also known.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carboranes are highly stable dodecahedral derivatives of the [B12H12]2- unit, with one BH replaced with a CH+.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Thus, the carbon is bonded to five boron atoms and one hydrogen atom.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The cation [(Ph3PAu)6C]2+ contains an octahedral carbon bound to six phosphine-gold fragments.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] This phenomenon has been attributed to the aurophilicity of the gold ligands, which provide additional stabilization of an otherwise labile species.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In nature, the iron-molybdenum cofactor (FeMoco) responsible for microbial nitrogen fixation likewise has an octahedral carbon center (formally a carbide, C(-IV)) bonded to six iron atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In 2016, it was confirmed that, in line with earlier theoretical predictions, the hexamethylbenzene dication contains a carbon atom with six bonds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] More specifically, the dication could be described structurally by the formulation [MeC(η5-C5Me5)]2+, making it an "organic metallocene" in which a MeC3+ fragment is bonded to a η5-C5Me5− fragment through all five of the carbons of the ring.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In the cases above, each of the bonds to carbon contain less than two formal electron pairs.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Thus, the formal electron count of these species does not exceed an octet.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] This makes them hypercoordinate but not hypervalent.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The English name *carbon* comes from the Latin *carbo* for coal and charcoal, whence also comes the French *charbon*, meaning charcoal.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In German, Dutch and Danish, the names for carbon are *Kohlenstoff*, *koolstof*, and *kulstof* respectively, all literally meaning coal-substance.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon was discovered in prehistory and was known in the forms of soot and charcoal to the earliest human civilizations.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Diamonds were known probably as early as 2500 BCE in China, while carbon in the form of charcoal was made by the same chemistry as it is today, by heating wood in a pyramid covered with clay to exclude air.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In 1722, René Antoine Ferchault de Réaumur demonstrated that iron was transformed into steel through the absorption of some substance, now known to be carbon.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In 1772, Antoine Lavoisier showed that diamonds are a form of carbon; when he burned samples of charcoal and diamond and found that neither produced any water and that both released the same amount of carbon dioxide per gram.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In 1779, Carl Wilhelm Scheele showed that graphite, which had been thought of as a form of lead, was instead identical with charcoal but with a small admixture of iron, and that it gave "aerial acid" (his name for carbon dioxide) when oxidized with nitric acid.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In 1786, the French scientists Claude Louis Berthollet, Gaspard Monge and C.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Vandermonde confirmed that graphite was mostly carbon by oxidizing it in oxygen in much the same way Lavoisier had done with diamond.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Some iron again was left, which the French scientists thought was necessary to the graphite structure.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In their publication they proposed the name *carbone* (Latin *carbonum*) for the element in graphite which was given off as a gas upon burning graphite.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Antoine Lavoisier then listed carbon as an element in his 1789 textbook.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] A new allotrope of carbon, fullerene, that was discovered in 1985 includes nanostructured forms such as buckyballs and nanotubes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Their discoverers – Robert Curl, Harold Kroto, and Richard Smalley – received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1996.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The resulting renewed interest in new forms led to the discovery of further exotic allotropes, including glassy carbon, and the realization that "amorphous carbon" is not strictly amorphous.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Commercially viable natural deposits of graphite occur in many parts of the world, but the most important sources economically are in China, India, Brazil, and North Korea.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Graphite deposits are of metamorphic origin, found in association with quartz, mica, and feldspars in schists, gneisses, and metamorphosed sandstones and limestone as lenses or veins, sometimes of a metre or more in thickness.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Deposits of graphite in Borrowdale, Cumberland, England were at first of sufficient size and purity that, until the 19th century, pencils were made by sawing blocks of natural graphite into strips before encasing the strips in wood.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Today, smaller deposits of graphite are obtained by crushing the parent rock and floating the lighter graphite out on water.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] There are three types of natural graphite—amorphous, flake or crystalline flake, and vein or lump.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Amorphous graphite is the lowest quality and most abundant.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Contrary to science, in industry "amorphous" refers to very small crystal size rather than complete lack of crystal structure.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Amorphous is used for lower value graphite products and is the lowest priced graphite.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Large amorphous graphite deposits are found in China, Europe, Mexico and the United States.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Flake graphite is less common and of higher quality than amorphous; it occurs as separate plates that crystallized in metamorphic rock.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Flake graphite can be four times the price of amorphous.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Good quality flakes can be processed into expandable graphite for many uses, such as flame retardants.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The foremost deposits are found in Austria, Brazil, Canada, China, Germany and Madagascar.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Vein or lump graphite is the rarest, most valuable, and highest quality type of natural graphite.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It occurs in veins along intrusive contacts in solid lumps, and it is only commercially mined in Sri Lanka.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] According to the USGS, world production of natural graphite was 1.1 million tonnes in 2010, to which China contributed 800,000 t, India 130,000 t, Brazil 76,000 t, North Korea 30,000 t and Canada 25,000 t.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] No natural graphite was reported mined in the United States, but 118,000 t of synthetic graphite with an estimated value of $998 million was produced in 2009.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The diamond supply chain is controlled by a limited number of powerful businesses, and is also highly concentrated in a small number of locations around the world (see figure).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Only a very small fraction of the diamond ore consists of actual diamonds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The ore is crushed, during which care has to be taken in order to prevent larger diamonds from being destroyed in this process and subsequently the particles are sorted by density.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Today, diamonds are located in the diamond-rich density fraction with the help of X-ray fluorescence, after which the final sorting steps are done by hand.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Before the use of X-rays became commonplace, the separation was done with grease belts; diamonds have a stronger tendency to stick to grease than the other minerals in the ore.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Historically diamonds were known to be found only in alluvial deposits in southern India.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Diamond production of primary deposits (kimberlites and lamproites) only started in the 1870s after the discovery of the diamond fields in South Africa.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Production has increased over time and an accumulated total of over 4.5 billion carats have been mined since that date.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Most commercially viable diamond deposits were in Russia, Botswana, Australia and the Democratic Republic of Congo.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] By 2005, Russia produced almost one-fifth of the global diamond output (mostly in Yakutia territory; for example, Mir pipe and Udachnaya pipe) but the Argyle mine in Australia became the single largest source, producing 14 million carats in 2018.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] New finds, the Canadian mines at Diavik and Ekati, are expected to become even more valuable owing to their production of gem quality stones.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In the United States, diamonds have been found in Arkansas, Colorado, and Montana.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In 2004, a startling discovery of a microscopic diamond in the United States led to the January 2008 bulk-sampling of kimberlite pipes in a remote part of Montana.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] While natural diamonds form over time deep within the Earth, synthetic diamonds are created in laboratories through a variety of methods.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The original method uses high pressure and high temperature (HPHT) and is still widely used because of its relatively low cost.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The process involves large presses that can weigh hundreds of tons to produce a pressure of 5 GPa (730,000 psi) at 1,500 °C (2,730 °F).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The second method, using chemical vapor deposition (CVD), creates a carbon plasma over a substrate onto which the carbon atoms deposit to form diamond.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Other methods include explosive formation (forming detonation nanodiamonds) and sonication of graphite solutions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon is essential to all known living systems, and without it life as we know it could not exist (see alternative biochemistry).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The major economic use of carbon other than food and wood is in the form of hydrocarbons, most notably the greenhouse gas and fossil fuel methane gas and crude oil (petroleum).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Crude oil is distilled in refineries by the petrochemical industry to produce gasoline, kerosene, and other products.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Cellulose is a natural, carbon-containing polymer produced by plants in the form of wood, cotton, linen, and hemp.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Cellulose is used primarily for maintaining structure in plants.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Commercially valuable carbon polymers of animal origin include wool, cashmere, and silk.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Plastics are made from synthetic carbon polymers, often with oxygen and nitrogen atoms included at regular intervals in the main polymer chain.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The raw materials for many of these synthetic substances come from crude oil and coal.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The uses of carbon and its compounds are extremely varied.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It can form alloys with iron, of which the most common is carbon steel.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Graphite is combined with clays to form the 'lead' used in pencils used for writing and drawing.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It is also used as a lubricant and a pigment, as a moulding material in glass manufacture, in electrodes for dry batteries and in electroplating and electroforming, in brushes for electric motors, and as a neutron moderator in nuclear reactors.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Charcoal is used as a drawing material in artwork, barbecue grilling, iron smelting, and in many other applications.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Wood, coal and oil are used as fuel for production of energy and heating.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Gem quality diamond is used in jewelry, and industrial diamonds are used in drilling, cutting and polishing tools for machining metals and stone.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon fiber, which is produced by pyrolyzing synthetic polyester fibers, is used to reinforce plastics, creating advanced, lightweight composite materials.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon fiber is made by pyrolysis of extruded and stretched filaments of polyacrylonitrile (PAN) and other organic substances.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The crystallographic structure and mechanical properties of the fiber depend on the type of starting material, and on the subsequent processing.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon fibers made from PAN have structure resembling narrow filaments of graphite, but thermal processing may re-order the structure into a continuous rolled sheet.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The result is fibers with higher specific tensile strength than steel.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon black is used as the black pigment in printing ink, artist's oil paint, and water colours, carbon paper, automotive finishes, India ink and laser printer toner.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon black is also used as a filler in rubber products such as tyres and in plastic compounds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Activated charcoal is used as an absorbent and adsorbent in filter material in applications as diverse as gas masks, water purification, and kitchen extractor hoods, and in medicine to absorb toxins, poisons, or gases from the digestive system.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon is used in chemical reduction at high temperatures.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Coke is used to reduce iron ore into iron (smelting).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Case hardening of steel is achieved by heating finished steel components in carbon powder.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbides of silicon, tungsten, boron, and titanium are among the hardest known materials, and are used as abrasives in cutting and grinding tools.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon compounds make up most of the materials used in clothing, such as natural and synthetic textiles and leather, and almost all of the interior surfaces in the built environment other than glass, stone, drywall, and metal.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The diamond industry falls into two categories: one dealing with gem-grade diamonds and the other, with industrial-grade diamonds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] While a large trade in both types of diamonds exists, the two markets function dramatically differently.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Unlike precious metals such as gold or platinum, gem diamonds do not trade as a commodity.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] There is a substantial mark-up in the sale of diamonds, and there is not a very active market for resale of diamonds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Industrial diamonds are valued mostly for their hardness and heat conductivity, with the gemological qualities of clarity and color being mostly irrelevant.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] About 80% of mined diamonds (equal to about 100 million carats or 20 tonnes annually) are unsuitable for use as gemstones and relegated for industrial use (known as *bort)*.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Synthetic diamonds, invented in the 1950s, found almost immediate industrial applications; 3 billion carats (600 tonnes) of synthetic diamond is produced annually.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The dominant industrial use of diamond is in cutting, drilling, grinding, and polishing.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Most of these applications do not require large diamonds; in fact, most diamonds of gem-quality except for their small size can be used industrially.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Diamonds are embedded in drill tips or saw blades, or ground into a powder for use in grinding and polishing applications.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Specialized applications include use in laboratories as containment for high-pressure experiments (see diamond anvil cell), high-performance bearings, and limited use in specialized windows.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] With the continuing advances in the production of synthetic diamonds, new applications are becoming feasible.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Garnering much excitement is the possible use of diamond as a semiconductor suitable for microchips, and because of its exceptional heat conductance property, as a heat sink in electronics.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Pure carbon has extremely low toxicity to humans and can be handled safely in the form of graphite or charcoal.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] It is resistant to dissolution or chemical attack, even in the acidic contents of the digestive tract.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Consequently, once it enters into the body's tissues it is likely to remain there indefinitely.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon black was probably one of the first pigments to be used for tattooing, and Ötzi the Iceman was found to have carbon tattoos that survived during his life and for 5200 years after his death.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Inhalation of coal dust or soot (carbon black) in large quantities can be dangerous, irritating lung tissues and causing the congestive lung disease, coalworker's pneumoconiosis.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Diamond dust used as an abrasive can be harmful if ingested or inhaled.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Microparticles of carbon are produced in diesel engine exhaust fumes, and may accumulate in the lungs.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] However, in these examples, the harm may result from contaminants (e.g., organic chemicals, heavy metals) rather than from the carbon itself.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Carbon may burn vigorously and brightly in the presence of air at high temperatures.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Large accumulations of coal, which have remained inert for hundreds of millions of years in the absence of oxygen, may spontaneously combust when exposed to air in coal mine waste tips, ship cargo holds and coal bunkers, and storage dumps.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] In nuclear applications where graphite is used as a neutron moderator, accumulation of Wigner energy followed by a sudden, spontaneous release may occur.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] Annealing to at least 250 °C can release the energy safely, although in the Windscale fire the procedure went wrong, causing other reactor materials to combust.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/carbon] The great variety of carbon compounds include such lethal poisons as tetrodotoxin, the lectin ricin from seeds of the castor oil plant *Ricinus communis*, cyanide (CN−), and carbon monoxide; and such essentials to life as glucose and protein.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] This registry includes all substances described since 1957, plus some substances from as far back as the early 1800s.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] It is a chemical database that includes organic and inorganic compounds, minerals, isotopes, alloys, mixtures, and nonstructurable materials (UVCBs - substances of **u**nknown or **v**ariable composition, **c**omplex reaction products, or **b**iological origin).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] CAS RNs are generally serial numbers (with a check digit), so they do not contain any information about the structures themselves the way SMILES and InChI strings do.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry is an authoritative collection of disclosed chemical substance information.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] It identifies more than 204 million unique organic and inorganic substances and 69 million protein and DNA sequences, plus additional information about each substance.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] It is updated with around 15,000 additional new substances daily.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] The full registry is available on a paid subscription basis.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] A collection of almost 500 thousand CAS registry numbers is made available under a CC BY-NC license at ACS Commons Chemistry.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] Historically, chemicals have been identified by a wide variety of synonyms and properties.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] One of the biggest challenges in the early development of substance indexing, a task undertaken by the Chemical Abstracts Service, was in identifying if a substance in literature was new or if it had been previously discovered.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] Well-known chemicals may be known via multiple generic, historical, commercial, and/or (black)-market names, and even systematic nomenclature based on structure alone was not universally useful.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] An algorithm was developed to translate the structural formula of a chemical into a computer-searchable table, which provided a basis for the service that listed each chemical with its CAS Registry Number, the CAS Chemical Registry System, which became operational in 1965.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] CAS Registry Numbers (CAS RN) are simple and regular, convenient for database searches.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] They offer a reliable, common and international link to every specific substance across the various nomenclatures and disciplines used by branches of science, industry, and regulatory bodies.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] Almost all molecule databases today allow searching by CAS Registry Number, and it is used as a global standard.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] A CAS Registry Number has no inherent meaning, but is assigned in sequential, increasing order when the substance is identified by CAS scientists for inclusion in the CAS Registry database.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] A CAS RN is separated by hyphens into three parts, the first consisting from two up to seven digits, the second consisting of two digits, and the third consisting of a single digit serving as a check digit.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] This format gives CAS a maximum capacity of 1,000,000,000 unique numbers.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] The check digit is found by taking the last digit times 1, the preceding digit times 2, the preceding digit times 3 etc., adding all these up and computing the sum modulo 10.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] The CAS Registry accepts entries that are (1) descriptive of matter consisting of chemical elements, (2) distinct from existing ones, and (3) present in scientific literature.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] The definition of "distinct" excludes different phases of the same substance (e.g. water and ice), but includes narrowing of existing concepts (e.g. carbon vs. graphite and diamond; isotope-labelled forms of an existing compound).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] The Chemical Abstracts Service subscription includes an official search service.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] The Service ("CAS Data") provides information on the chemical itself, its mentions in published scholarly works and patents, curated biological and chemical reaction data, as well as listings of commercial sources and details on using a substance in a formulation.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/cas-registry-number] A subset of the registry can be accessed through the free-of-charge CAS Common Chemistry, which provides identifying information for the chemical in question.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] These are limited to a single typographic line of symbols, which may include subscripts and superscripts.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] A chemical formula is not a chemical name since it does not contain any words.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Although a chemical formula may imply certain simple chemical structures, it is not the same as a full chemical structural formula.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae can fully specify the structure of only the simplest of molecules and chemical substances, and are generally more limited in power than chemical names and structural formulae.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The simplest types of chemical formulae are called *empirical formulae*, which use letters and numbers indicating the numerical *proportions* of atoms of each type.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] **Molecular formulae** indicate the simple numbers of each type of atom in a molecule, with no information on structure.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, the empirical formula for glucose is CH2O (twice as many hydrogen atoms as carbon and oxygen), while its molecular formula is C6H12O6 (12 hydrogen atoms, six carbon and oxygen atoms).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] This is possible if the relevant bonding is easy to show in one dimension.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] An example is the condensed molecular/chemical formula for ethanol, which is CH3−CH2−OH or CH3CH2OH.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] However, even a condensed chemical formula is necessarily limited in its ability to show complex bonding relationships between atoms, especially atoms that have bonds to four or more different substituents.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For reasons of structural complexity, a single condensed chemical formula (or semi-structural formula) may correspond to different molecules, known as isomers.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, glucose shares its molecular formula C6H12O6 with a number of other sugars, including fructose, galactose and mannose.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Linear equivalent chemical *names* exist that can and do specify uniquely any complex structural formula (see chemical nomenclature), but such names must use many terms (words), rather than the simple element symbols, numbers, and simple typographical symbols that define a chemical formula.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae may be used in chemical equations to describe chemical reactions and other chemical transformations, such as the dissolving of ionic compounds into solution.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] A chemical formula identifies each constituent element by its chemical symbol and indicates the proportionate number of atoms of each element.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] In empirical formulae, these proportions begin with a key element and then assign numbers of atoms of the other elements in the compound, by ratios to the key element.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For molecular compounds, these ratio numbers can all be expressed as whole numbers.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, the empirical formula of ethanol may be written C2H6O because the molecules of ethanol all contain two carbon atoms, six hydrogen atoms, and one oxygen atom.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Some types of ionic compounds, however, cannot be written with entirely whole-number empirical formulae.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] An example is boron carbide, whose formula of CB*n* is a variable non-whole number ratio with n ranging from over 4 to more than 6.5.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] When the chemical compound of the formula consists of simple molecules, chemical formulae often employ ways to suggest the structure of the molecule.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] These types of formulae are variously known as *molecular formulae* and *condensed formulae*.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] A molecular formula enumerates the number of atoms to reflect those in the molecule, so that the molecular formula for glucose is C6H12O6 rather than the glucose empirical formula, which is CH2O.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] However, except for very simple substances, molecular chemical formulae lack needed structural information, and are ambiguous.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For simple molecules, a condensed (or semi-structural) formula is a type of chemical formula that may fully imply a correct structural formula.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, ethanol may be represented by the condensed chemical formula CH3CH2OH, and dimethyl ether by the condensed formula CH3OCH3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] These two molecules have the same empirical and molecular formulae (C2H6O), but may be differentiated by the condensed formulae shown, which are sufficient to represent the full structure of these simple organic compounds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Condensed chemical formulae may also be used to represent ionic compounds that do not exist as discrete molecules, but nonetheless do contain covalently bound clusters within them.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] These polyatomic ions are groups of atoms that are covalently bound together and have an overall ionic charge, such as the sulfate [SO4]2− ion.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Each polyatomic ion in a compound is written individually in order to illustrate the separate groupings.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, the compound dichlorine hexoxide has an empirical formula ClO3, and molecular formula Cl2O6, but in liquid or solid forms, this compound is more correctly shown by an ionic condensed formula [ClO2]+[ClO4]−, which illustrates that this compound consists of [ClO2]+ ions and [ClO4]− ions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] In such cases, the condensed formula only need be complex enough to show at least one of each ionic species.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae as described here are distinct from the far more complex chemical systematic names that are used in various systems of chemical nomenclature.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] This name, interpreted by the rules behind it, fully specifies glucose's structural formula, but the name is not a chemical formula as usually understood, and uses terms and words not used in chemical formulae.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Such names, unlike basic formulae, may be able to represent full structural formulae without graphs.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] In chemistry, the empirical formula of a chemical is a simple expression of the relative number of each type of atom or ratio of the elements in the compound.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Empirical formulae are the standard for ionic compounds, such as CaCl2, and for macromolecules, such as SiO2.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] An empirical formula makes no reference to isomerism, structure, or absolute number of atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The term *empirical* refers to the process of elemental analysis, a technique of analytical chemistry used to determine the relative percent composition of a pure chemical substance by element.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, hexane has a molecular formula of C6H14, and (for one of its isomers, n-hexane) a structural formula CH3CH2CH2CH2CH2CH3, implying that it has a chain structure of 6 carbon atoms, and 14 hydrogen atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] However, the empirical formula for hexane is C3H7.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Likewise the empirical formula for hydrogen peroxide, H2O2, is simply HO, expressing the 1:1 ratio of component elements.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Formaldehyde and acetic acid have the same empirical formula, CH2O.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] This is also the molecular formula for formaldehyde, but acetic acid has double the number of atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Like the other formula types detailed below, an empirical formula shows the number of elements in a molecule, and determines whether it is a binary compound, ternary compound, quaternary compound, or has even more elements.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Molecular formulae simply indicate the numbers of each type of atom in a molecule of a molecular substance.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] They are the same as empirical formulae for molecules that only have one atom of a particular type, but otherwise may have larger numbers.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] An example of the difference is the empirical formula for glucose, which is CH2O (*ratio* 1:2:1), while its molecular formula is C6H12O6 (*number of atoms* 6:12:6).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] A molecular formula provides more information about a molecule than its empirical formula, but is more difficult to establish.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] In addition to indicating the number of atoms of each elementa molecule, a structural formula indicates how the atoms are organized, and shows (or implies) the chemical bonds between the atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] There are multiple types of structural formulas focused on different aspects of the molecular structure.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The two diagrams show two molecules which are structural isomers of each other, since they both have the same molecular formula C4H10, but they have different structural formulas as shown.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The connectivity of a molecule often has a strong influence on its physical and chemical properties and behavior.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Two molecules composed of the same numbers of the same types of atoms (i.e. a pair of isomers) might have completely different chemical and/or physical properties if the atoms are connected differently or in different positions.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] In such cases, a structural formula is useful, as it illustrates which atoms are bonded to which other ones.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] From the connectivity, it is often possible to deduce the approximate shape of the molecule.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] A condensed (or semi-structural) formula may represent the types and spatial arrangement of bonds in a simple chemical substance, though it does not necessarily specify isomers or complex structures.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, ethane consists of two carbon atoms single-bonded to each other, with each carbon atom having three hydrogen atoms bonded to it.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Its chemical formula can be rendered as CH3CH3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] In ethylene there is a double bond between the carbon atoms (and thus each carbon only has two hydrogens), therefore the chemical formula may be written: CH2CH2, and the fact that there is a double bond between the carbons is implicit because carbon has a valence of four.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] However, a more explicit method is to write H2C=CH2 or less commonly H2C::CH2.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The two lines (or two pairs of dots) indicate that a double bond connects the atoms on either side of them.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] A triple bond may be expressed with three lines (HC≡CH) or three pairs of dots (HC:::CH), and if there may be ambiguity, a single line or pair of dots may be used to indicate a single bond.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Molecules with multiple functional groups that are the same may be expressed by enclosing the repeated group in round brackets.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, isobutane may be written (CH3)3CH.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] This condensed structural formula implies a different connectivity from other molecules that can be formed using the same atoms in the same proportions (isomers).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The formula (CH3)3CH implies a central carbon atom connected to one hydrogen atom and three methyl groups (CH3).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The same number of atoms of each element (10 hydrogens and 4 carbons, or C4H10) may be used to make a straight chain molecule, *n*-butane: CH3CH2CH2CH3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The International Union of Crystallography (IUCr) has proposed a crystal-chemical formula notation that extends standard formulae with optional annotations for these items.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The alkene called but-2-ene has two isomers, which the chemical formula CH3CH=CHCH3 does not identify.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The relative position of the two methyl groups must be indicated by additional notation denoting whether the methyl groups are on the same side of the double bond (*cis* or *Z*) or on the opposite sides from each other (*trans* or *E*).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] As noted above, in order to represent the full structural formulae of many complex organic and inorganic compounds, chemical nomenclature may be needed which goes well beyond the available resources used above in simple condensed formulae.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] See IUPAC nomenclature of organic chemistry and IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry 2005 for examples.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] In addition, linear naming systems such as International Chemical Identifier (InChI) allow a computer to construct a structural formula, and simplified molecular-input line-entry system (SMILES) allows a more human-readable ASCII input.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] However, all these nomenclature systems go beyond the standards of chemical formulae, and technically are chemical naming systems, not formula systems.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For polymers in condensed chemical formulae, parentheses are placed around the repeating unit.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, a hydrocarbon molecule that is described as CH3(CH2)50CH3, is a molecule with fifty repeating units.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] If the number of repeating units is unknown or variable, the letter *n* may be used to indicate this formula: CH3(CH2)*n*CH3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For ions, the charge on a particular atom may be denoted with a right-hand superscript.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The total charge on a charged molecule or a polyatomic ion may also be shown in this way, such as for hydronium, H3O+, or sulfate, SO2−4.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Here + and − are used in place of +1 and −1, respectively.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For more complex ions, brackets [ ] are often used to enclose the ionic formula, as in [B12H12]2−, which is found in compounds such as caesium dodecaborate, Cs2[B12H12].
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Parentheses ( ) can be nested inside brackets to indicate a repeating unit, as in Hexamminecobalt(III) chloride, [Co(NH3)6]3+Cl−3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Here, (NH3)6 indicates that the ion contains six ammine groups (NH3) bonded to cobalt, and [ ] encloses the entire formula of the ion with charge +3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] This is strictly optional; a chemical formula is valid with or without ionization information, and Hexamminecobalt(III) chloride may be written as [Co(NH3)6]3+Cl−3 or [Co(NH3)6]Cl3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Brackets, like parentheses, behave in chemistry as they do in mathematics, grouping terms together – they are not specifically employed only for ionization states.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] In the latter case here, the parentheses indicate 6 groups all of the same shape, bonded to another group of size 1 (the cobalt atom), and then the entire bundle, as a group, is bonded to 3 chlorine atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] In the former case, it is clearer that the bond connecting the chlorines is ionic, rather than covalent.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Although isotopes are more relevant to nuclear chemistry or stable isotope chemistry than to conventional chemistry, different isotopes may be indicated with a prefixed superscript in a chemical formula.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, the phosphate ion containing radioactive phosphorus-32 is [32PO4]3−.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Also a study involving stable isotope ratios might include the molecule 18O16O.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] A left-hand subscript is sometimes used redundantly to indicate the atomic number.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, 8O2 for dioxygen, and 16 8O 2 for the most abundant isotopic species of dioxygen.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] This is convenient when writing equations for nuclear reactions, in order to show the balance of charge more clearly.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The @ symbol (at sign) indicates an atom or molecule trapped inside a cage but not chemically bound to it.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, a buckminsterfullerene (C60) with an atom (M) would simply be represented as MC60 regardless of whether M was inside the fullerene without chemical bonding or outside, bound to one of the carbon atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Using the @ symbol, this would be denoted M@C60 if M was inside the carbon network.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] A non-fullerene example is [As@Ni12As20]3−, an ion in which one arsenic (As) atom is trapped in a cage formed by the other 32 atoms.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] This notation was proposed in 1991 with the discovery of fullerene cages (endohedral fullerenes), which can trap atoms such as La to form, for example, La@C60 or La@C82.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The choice of the symbol has been explained by the authors as being concise, readily printed and transmitted electronically (the at sign is included in ASCII, which most modern character encoding schemes are based on), and the visual aspects suggesting the structure of an endohedral fullerene.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae most often use integers for each element.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] However, there is a class of compounds, called non-stoichiometric compounds, that cannot be represented by small integers.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Such a formula might be written using decimal fractions, as in Fe0.95O, or it might include a variable part represented by a letter, as in Fe1−*x*O, where *x* is normally much less than 1.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] A chemical formula used for a series of compounds that differ from each other by a constant unit is called a *general formula*.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] It generates a homologous series of chemical formulae.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] For example, alcohols may be represented by the formula C*n*H2*n* + 1OH (*n* ≥ 1), giving the homologs methanol, ethanol, propanol for 1 ≤ *n* ≤ 3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] When the formula contains no carbon, all the elements, including hydrogen, are listed alphabetically.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] The Hill system was first published by Edwin A.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] Hill of the United States Patent and Trademark Office in 1900.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] It is the most commonly used system in chemical databases and printed indexes to sort lists of compounds.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/chemical-formula] A list of formulae in Hill system order is arranged alphabetically, as above, with single-letter elements coming before two-letter symbols when the symbols begin with the same letter (so "B" comes before "Be", which comes before "Br").
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] The **DrugBank** database is a comprehensive, freely accessible, online database containing information on drugs and drug targets created and maintained by the University of Alberta and The Metabolomics Innovation Centre (TMIC) located in Alberta, Canada.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] As both a bioinformatics and a cheminformatics resource, DrugBank combines detailed drug (i.e. chemical, pharmacological and pharmaceutical) data with comprehensive drug target (i.e. sequence, structure, and pathway) information.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] DrugBank has used content from Wikipedia; Wikipedia also often links to Drugbank, posing potential circular reporting issues.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] The DrugBank Online website is available to the public as a free-to-access resource.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] However, use and re-distribution of content from DrugBank Online or the underlying DrugBank Data, in whole or part, and for any purpose requires a license.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Academic users can apply for a free license for certain use cases while all other users require a paid license.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] The latest release of the database (version 6.0) contains 11,891 drug entries including 4030 FDA-approved small molecule drugs, 1601 FDA-approved biotech (protein/peptide) drugs, 134 nutraceuticals and 6722 experimental drugs.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Additionally, 4939 non-redundant protein (i.e. drug target/enzyme/transporter/carrier) sequences are linked to these drug entries.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Each DrugCard entry contains more than 200 data fields with half of the information being devoted to drug/chemical data and the other half devoted to drug target or protein data.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Four additional databases, HMDB, T3DB, SMPDB and FooDB are also part of a general suite of metabolomic/cheminformatic databases.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] The first version of DrugBank was released in 2006.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] This early release contained relatively modest information about 841 FDA-approved small molecule drugs and 113 biotech drugs.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] It also included information on 2133 drug targets.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] The second version of DrugBank was released in 2009.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] This greatly expanded and improved version of the database included 1344 approved small molecule drugs and 123 biotech drugs as well as 3037 unique drug targets.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Version 2.0 also included, for the first time, withdrawn drugs and illicit drugs, extensive food-drug and drug-drug interactions as well as ADMET (absorption, distribution, metabolism, excretion and toxicity) parameters.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] This version contained 1424 approved small molecule drugs and 132 biotech drugs as well as >4000 unique drug targets.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Version 3.0 also included drug transporter data, drug pathway data, drug pricing, patent and manufacturing data as well as data on >5000 experimental drugs.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] This version included 1558 FDA-approved small molecule drugs, 155 biotech drugs and 4200 unique drug targets.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Version 4.0 also incorporated extensive information on drug metabolites (structures and reactions), drug taxonomy, drug spectra, drug binding constants and drug synthesis information.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] This version included 2100 FDA-approved small molecule drugs, 555 biotech drugs, 4563 unique drug targets.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Version 5 also incorporated new data types that captures the influence of drugs on metabolite (pharmaco-metabolomic), protein (pharmaco-proteomic) and gene expression (pharmaco-transcriptomic) levels.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Version 5 also added mobile device compatibility, better searching tools, data on clinical trials and drug repurposing efforts and for the first time, images of pills or medication.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] In addition to the number of drug entries reported above, the number of FDA-approved drugs and investigational drugs had grown compared to Version 5.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] There was a large increase in the number drug-drug and drug-food interactions reported.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] The number of drug metabolism pathways grew substantially from 64 in Version 5 to 2721 with this last release.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Experimental as well as predicted MS/MS, NMR spectra, Collision Cross Section (CCS- for MS), retention indices (RI, for gas chromatography) and retention time (RT, for liquid chromatography) were added for the small molecule drugs.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Table 1 provides a more complete statistical summary of the history of DrugBank's development.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] All data in DrugBank is derived from public non-proprietary sources.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] Nearly every data item is fully traceable and explicitly referenced to the original source.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/drugbank] DrugBank data is available through a public web interface.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] The **European Community number** (**EC number**) is a unique seven-digit identifier that was assigned to substances for regulatory purposes within the European Union by the European Commission.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] The *EC Inventory* comprises three individual inventories, EINECS, ELINCS and the NLP list.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] The EC number may be written in a general form as: NNN-NNN-R, where the N represents digits and R is a check digit.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] The check digit is calculated using the ISBN method.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] If the remainder R is equal to 10, that combination of digits is not used for an EC number.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] To illustrate, the EC number of dexamethasone is 200-003-9.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] N1 is 2, N2 through N5 are 0, and N6 is 3.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] The remainder is 9, which is the check digit.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] There is a set of 181 ELINCS numbers (EC numbers starting with 4) for which the checksum by the above algorithm is 10 and the number has not been skipped but issued with a checksum of 1.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] The EC Inventory includes the substances in the following inventories.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] The content of these inventories is fixed and official.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] The European Chemicals Agency (ECHA) applies a format similar to the EC number to what it calls "List number".
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] The number is assigned under the REACH and CLP regulations without being legally recognised.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] They are not considered official identifiers because they have not been published in the Official Journal of the European Union.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] List numbers are administrative tools and shall not be used for any official purposes.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] List numbers have alphanumerical format and same length as EC numbers (xxx-xxx-x).
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] A list number assigned by ECHA starts with 1, 6, 7, 8, 9, or a letter.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] Earlier, list numbers shared the same format with EC numbers.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] However, as numbers in that format ran out at the end of 2025, the list number format became alphanumerical.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] The new format retains the same length but begins with a letter instead of a digit.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] Once all letters in alphabetical order have been used as the first character, the second character will become a letter, and so on.
[src:n-formylmethionine-data-page/einecs-number] List numbers assigned before the format change in December 2025 will remain unchangedstay and are not affected by the new format.
